notesStmt.note: Yitsḥaḳ ben Yudah of Tulusa (Toulouse): inscribed with his name on the frontispiece and in the colophon, Solsona , Kislew 5145 [1384] (folios 2v, 427r).
Laurentius D'Arvieux (b. 1635, d. 1702), French traveller and diplomat, consul for France and Holland at Aleppo: Latin title page added by him (folio 1r); purchased in 1683.
Latin account on the history of the manuscript, 16th century (folio 1v).
Benjamin Kennicott (b. 1718, d. 1783), English biblical scholar: his translation of the Latin account on folio 1v, 1768 (a paper sheet affixed on folio [i verso]).
King George III (b. 1738, d. 1820): his stamp on upper and lower covers.
Manuscript description based on Margoliouth, G.: Catalogue of the Hebrew and Samaritan Manuscripts in the British Museum, London 1965.

msContents.summary: Bible (the 'King's Bible'), with vowel-points and accents.

layoutDesc.layout: Columns: 2; ruled lines: 32; written lines: 32; Uniform layout. Ruling and pricking are visible. Flesh and hair side are distinguishable. Pagination and decorated chapter numbers - both with Hebrew characters - are later additions (after 1683). Remains of inscriptions probably printed from another consecutive page presently missing, upside down and right to left ( folio [i recto]). Numerous decorations: 1 full-page frontispiece, 2 full-page miniatures of Temple implements, 3 full-page miniatures in colours and gold. Numerous decorated initial-word panels and chapter numbers. In the Pentateuch the masorah parva is frequently added in the margins and between the columns. Joshua 1-2 is provided with the masorah magna and parva, as well as Judges 16 to 1Samuel 11 (folios 127v-136r). Judges, Samuel, Jonah, Habakuk, Psalms, and Ecclesiastes begin a new column, and Deuteronomy, Nahum, Zechariah, Malachi and Lamentations begin a new leaf.

scriptDesc.scriptNote: Sefardi square script, last quarter of 14th century, punctuated. Ya῾aḳov ben Yosef of Ripoll: inscribed with his name in the colophon, Solsona, Kislew 5145 [1384] (folio 427r).

binding.p: Post-1600. Red leather, 18th century, gold tooled with the monogram of George III. Spine: 'Biblia Hebraica.'

history.provenance: Acquisition: Given to the British Museum by King George IV in 1823 as part of the library of King George III.
